<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">

<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta http-equiv="X-UA-Compatible" content="IE=edge">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="css/styles.css">
    <title>To Do List</title>
</head>

<body>

    <h1>
        <%= listTitle %>
    </h1>

    <ul> 
        <% for (let i=0; i < lisOfItems.length; i++) { %>
            <li>
                <%= lisOfItems[i] %>
            </li>
            <% } %>
    </ul>

    <!-- Submit button will make a post request to the home route -->
    <!-- In this example, the form element specifies the target URL for the form submission using the action attribute. The
    method attribute specifies the HTTP method to use for the submission, which in this case is post.

    The input element with type="submit" creates a button that, when clicked, will submit the form. The value attribute
    sets the text that will be displayed on the button.

    When the form is submitted, it will make a POST request to the home route (i.e., the root URL of your website). You
    can handle this request on the server side using the appropriate framework or technology. -->
    <form class="" action="/" method="post">
        <input type="text" name="newItem">
        <button type="submit" name="button">Add</button>
    </form>




</body>

</html>